content: Ah, the buzz of NYC! The city's energy is electric, even the pigeons seem more ambitious here. Just had my first coffee back in the Big Apple.
Caught up with old contacts. Networking now to secure that dream job at a quant firm. The city's pace is a reminder to keep pushing.
Reflections on turning 22: This year's about finding balance. Balancing ambition with learning, failure with growth. It's a pivotal time.
Spent the last few days diving into machine learning models. Predictive analytics in trading is fascinating. Learning curve's steep but exciting.
Meeting with a mentor today. Discussing ethical trading strategies. Want to ensure my career aligns with my values.
Had an interview for that quant firm. Felt like a mix of excitement and a test of endurance. Fingers crossed, but I'm prepared for all outcomes.
My side project is taking shape. Developing algorithms that minimize market volatility feels like a small step towards a more sustainable future.
Setback: An algorithm I was working on crashed. Back to the drawing board, but this time with a clearer understanding of where it went wrong.
Joined a meetup on sustainable trading. Shared ideas, got feedback. The community here is inspiring, pushing me to think outside the box.
Second interview at the quant firm. More technical, focused on my understanding of AI in trading. It's a marathon, not a sprint.
Progress on the side project. Integrated new data sets to test volatility reduction. It's promising but needs refinement.
Visited a mentor, discussed emotional resilience in trading. Learning to detach from losses and see them as part of the journey, not the end.
Received feedback on my project. Some of the algorithms are showing potential, but I need to work on scalability. Back to the books.
The job hunt's a rollercoaster. Got an offer from a different firm, but it's not the dream. Debating if it's a stepping stone or a detour.
Another round of testing on my project. The numbers are looking better, but it's a slow grind. Patience is key in both trading and development.
Celebrated a small victory. An algorithm I tweaked significantly reduced volatility in a simulated environment. Feels like progress.
Reflecting on the past few weeks, the journey's been a mix of highs and lows. Learning to embrace the process, not just the destination.
A mentor's advice hit home: "Success in trading is as much about managing yourself as it is about managing algorithms." Time to work on that.
Just finished a marathon session on the side project. Scalability's still a puzzle, but I'm piecing together a solution using distributed computing. #Growth
Spent the last few days with my mentor, discussing how AI can promote fairness in trading. It's not just about efficiency—it's about equity.
The interview process at the quant firm's like a chess game. Each move counts. Prepping for the next round, focusing on ethical AI integration.
Got some feedback on my sustainable trading algorithm. It's like playing a game where the rules are constantly changing, but I'm adapting.
Had a breakthrough on my side project. Implemented a new strategy that reduces market volatility by 15% in simulations. Baby steps to a sustainable future.
Interview prep took a turn. Asked about how to balance speed and fairness in trading. The more I think about it, the more complex it becomes.
Connected with a mentor from Asia. Discussed the unique trading dynamics there, integrating these insights into my pitch. Cultural nuances matter.
Back to the drawing board on my project. The latest iteration introduced some bugs. Debugging's like detective work, finding the culprit in the code.
Received an invitation to present my project at a sustainable finance conference. It's a chance to get real-world validation. Excitement and nerves mix.
Attended a workshop on emotional resilience in trading. Learning to treat losses as data points, not personal failures. It's a mindset shift.
Another round of testing on my project. This time, the results are promising. The algorithm's handling volatility like a seasoned trader.
Had a deep conversation with a mentor about the ethical implications of AI in trading. It's not just about making money; it's about making a difference.
The quant firm interview's getting intense. They're asking about my approach to risk management. Integrating lessons from past losses.
Spent the last few days enhancing my network in the sustainable finance sector. Attended a panel, made connections, and got some advice on my project.
The conference presentation went well. Got some critical feedback on my project, but also interest from potential collaborators. Progress!
Got the call from the quant firm. They want me for another interview, this time to discuss my project's real-world application. The journey continues.
